revision.text:
{{Italic title}}
{{About|literary use of the phrase|1917 painting by Paul Klee|Ab ovo (painting)|biological alternative to spontaneous generation|Omne vivum ex ovo}}
[[File:Leda and the Swan 1505-1510.jpg|thumb|''Leda and the Swan'', a painting depicting Helen's unconventional birth, by [[Cesare da Sesto]] (c.&nbsp;1506&ndash;1510, [[Wilton, Wiltshire|Wilton]]) after a lost painting by [[Leonardo da Vinci]]. Helen and [[Clytemnestra]] are shown emerging from one egg; [[Castor and Pollux]] from another.]]
'''''Ab ovo''''' ([[Latin]]: "from the beginning, the origin, the [[egg (biology)|egg]]") is a reference to one of the twin eggs from which [[Helen of Troy#Birth|Helen of Troy was born]]. The eggs were laid by [[Leda (mythology)|Leda]] after mating with [[Zeus]] disguised as a swan. Had [[Leda (mythology)|Leda]] not laid the egg, [[Helen of Troy|Helen]] would not have been born, so [[Paris (mythology)|Paris]] could not have eloped with her, so there would have been no [[Trojan War]].<ref>Helen of Troy: From Homer to Hollywood. John Wiley & Sons, Ltd. Chichester, West Sussex, U.K.</ref>

== In literature ==

The [[English language|English]] literary use of the phrase comes from [[Horace]]'s ''[[Ars Poetica (Horace)|Ars Poetica]]'', where he describes his ideal epic poet as one who "does not begin the Trojan War from the double egg" (''nec gemino bellum Troianum orditur ab ouo''), the absolute beginning of events, the earliest possible chronological point, but snatches the listener into the middle of things (''[[in medias res]]''). This advice is famously rejected in [[Laurence Sterne]]'s novel [[The Life and Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman]].

This use is distinct from the longer phrase ''[[ab ovo usque ad mala]]'' (lit. "from the egg to the apples") which appears in Horace's [[Sermonum liber primus|''Satire'']] 1.3.  It refers to the course of a Roman meal, which often began with eggs and ended with fruit, and is similar to the American English phrase "[[wikt:from soup to nuts#Adverb|soup to nuts]]".  Thus ''ab ovo'' can also be used to mean a complete or entire thing.

